all_paragraphs: In this article I really want to give a look at the TensorFlow.js APIs and understand the library as a whole and understand what are the amazing things it has to offer to the machine learning community.

I know this article should be 5 minutes long but don’t worry it will not take more than 5 minutes to understand the obvious APIs and even though many of them are very obvious from there names, it was important for me to keep it beginner friendly.
I have kept the rest of the article as to-the-point as possible with examples. But If you guys have any doubt, let’s have discussion in the comments.
It will help you to write better & versatile machine learning code for any new future projects.
The APIs help to create things like tensors, clones etc.
Creates a Tensor with the specified shape of data type.
Note: They also have shape specified APIs like tf.tensor1d, tf.tensor2d, tf.tensor3d and tf.tensor4d.
Creates a Tensor with evenly spaced numbers.
Convert a set of sparse labels to a dense one-hot representation.
Prints the info. about any Tensor.
Creates a Tensor variable with provided initial value.
Flatten a Tensor to a 1D array
Converts a size-1 tf.Tensor to a tf.Scalar.
Converts a tf.Tensor to a tf.Tensor1D.
Converts a tf.Tensor to a tf.Tensor2D.
Converts a tf.Tensor to a tf.Tensor3D.
Converts a tf.Tensor to a tf.Tensor4D.
Casts a tf.Tensor to a specified dtype.
Returns a tf.TensorBuffer that holds the underlying data.
The tf.data API helps to build flexible and efficient input pipelines.
Casts the array to type float32.
Casts the array to type int32.
Casts the array to type bool.
Reshapes the tensor into the shape of the provided tensor.
Returns a human-readable description of the tensor. Useful for logging.
Assign a new tf.Tensor to this variable.
tf.TensorBuffer allows to set a value before declaring it a tf.Tensor whoch can’t be changed.
Sets a value in the buffer at a given location.
Returns the value in the buffer at the provided location.
Creates an immutable tf.Tensor object from the buffer.
Returns a tf.Tensor that has expanded rank, by inserting a dimension into the tensor’s shape.
Casts a tf.Tensor to a new dtype.
Pads a tf.Tensor with a given value and paddings.
Reshapes a tf.Tensor to a given shape.
Removes dimensions of size 1 from the shape of a tf.Tensor
Models are a collection of Layers, see Model Creation for details about how Layers can be connected.
27 - tf.model ( ) EXTENDS to CONTAINERS
A model is a data structure that consists of Layers and have nodes defined as inputs and outputs.
Models made with tf.model are just more generic than tf.sequential models.
The following code snippet defines a model consisting of two dense layers (fully connected), with 10 and 4 units.

Configures and prepares the model for training and evaluation. Compiling outfits the model with an config (optimizer, loss, and/or metrics). Calling fit or evaluate on an un-compiled model will throw an error.
Returns the loss value & metrics values for the model in test mode which are specified during compile(), which needs to happen before calls to evaluate().
Generates output predictions for the input samples and the computations is done in batches.
Returns predictions for a single batch of samples where x is a tensor.
Trains the model for a fixed number of epochs (iterations on a dataset).

29 - tf.loadModel ( path or IOHandler )
Load a model, including its topology and optionally weights.
Example 1: Save tf.model()’s topology and weights to browser local storage; then load it back.
Example 2: Load a model from user-selected files from HTML file input elements.
Example 3: Load a model from an HTTP server.
Copy a model from one URL to another.
List all models stored in registered storage mediums.
Move a model from one URL to another.
Remove a model specified by URL from a registered storage medium.
Input shape: Arbitrary. Use the configuration inputShape when using this layer as the first layer in a model.
Output shape→ Same shape as the input.

Creates a dense (fully connected) layer.
output = acticvation(dot(input, kernel(aka weights) ) + bias)
units (number) Positive integer, dimensionality of the output space.
rate (number) Float between 0 and 1. Fraction of the input units to drop.
Flattens the input and does not affect the batch size.
It flattens each batch in its inputs to 1D (making the output 2D).
This layer creates a convolution kernel that is convolved with the layer input to produce a tensor of outputs.
filters (number) The dimensionality of the output space (i.e. the number of filters in the convolution).
This layer can crop an input at the top, bottom, left and right side of an image tensor.
cropping (number|[number, number]|[[number, number], [number, number]])Dimension of the cropping along the width and the height.
Normalize the activations of the previous layer at each batch, i.e. applies a transformation that maintains the mean activation close to 0 and the activation standard deviation close to 1.
axis (number) The integer axis that should be normalized (typically the features axis). Defaults to -1.
Average pooling operation for spatial data.
poolSize (number or [number, number]) Factors by which to downscale in each dimension [vertical, horizontal]. Expects an integer or an array of 2 integers.
Note: They also have averagePooling1d and globalAveragePooling etc.
Max pooling operation for spatial data.
poolSize (number|[number, number]) Factors by which to downscale in each dimension [vertical, horizontal]. Expects an integer or an array of 2 integers.
Note: They also have maxPooling1d and globalMaxPooling etc.

It involves duplicating the first recurrent layer in the network so that there are now two layers side-by-side, then providing the input sequence as-is as input to the first layer and providing a reversed copy of the input sequence to the second. This technique helps in LSTMs.
layer (RNN) The instance of an RNN layer to be wrapped.
The input should be at least 3D, and the dimension of the index 1 will be considered to be the temporal dimension.
Input shape: 3D tensor with shape .
Computes the next states and outputs of a stack of LSTMCells.
Each cell output is used as input to the next cell
data The input to the cell.
c Array of previous cell states.
h Array of previous cell outputs.
Note: They also have tf.layers.simpleRNNCell ,

LSTM Cell is distinct from the RNN subclass LSTM in that its apply method takes the input data of only a single time step and returns the cell's output at the time step, while LSTM takes the input data over a number of time steps.
The most typical use of LSTMCell workflow is to combine a number of cells into a stacked RNN cell. For Example

Computes the next state and output of a BasicLSTMCell.

Constructs a tf.RMSPropOptimizer that uses RMSProp gradient descent.
learningRate (number) The learning rate to use for the RMSProp gradient descent algorithm.
decay (number) The discounting factor for the history/coming gradient. Optional
momentum (number) The momentum to use for the RMSProp gradient descent algorithm. Optional

centered (boolean) If true, gradients are normalized by the estimated variance of the gradient. Optional
49 - tf.losses.meanSquaredError (labels, predictions, weights?, reduction?)
Computes the mean squared error between two tensors.
50 - tf.losses.softmaxCrossEntropy ( labels , logits , dim? )
Computes softmax cross entropy between logits and labels. It measures the probability error in discrete classification tasks in which the classes are mutually exclusive.
For example, each CIFAR-10 image is labeled with one and only one label: an image can be a dog or a truck, but not both.
Executes the provided function f and after it is executed, cleans up all intermediate tensors allocated by f except those returned by f.
Using this method helps avoid memory leaks. In general, wrap calls to operations in tf.tidy() for automatic memory cleanup.
Keeps a tf.Tensor generated inside a tf.tidy() from being disposed automatically.
Returns memory info at the current time in the program.
Executes f( ) and returns a promise that resolves with timing information.
tf.setBackend ( backendType , safeMode? )
Sets the backend (cpu, webgl, etc) responsible for creating tensors and executing operations on those tensors.
Draws a tf.Tensor of pixel values to a byte array or optionally a canvas.
Also, When the dtype of the input is ‘float32’, we assume values in the range [0–1]. Otherwise, when input is ‘int32’, we assume values in the range [0–255].
canvas (HTMLCanvasElement) The canvas to draw to. Optional
img (tf.Tensor2D or tf.Tensor3D) A rank-2 or rank-3 tensor. If rank-2, draws grayscale. If rank-3, must have depth of 1, 3 or 4. When depth of 1, draws grayscale.
